<h3>Domain Repetition</h3>

<p>
  Since SDFs are expressed as mathematical functions, they can be transformed to
  repeat periodically across space. This technique, known as
  <strong>Domain Repetition</strong>, allows for the creation of infinite,
  repeating patterns while also optimizing performance by avoiding the need for
  multiple individual primitives.
</p>

<p>
  Trigonometric functions such as sin and cos create natural repetitive patterns,
  however bending the domain with these functions compromises the accurate
  Euclidean distances the SDF relies on, potentially generating undesired
  features. Functions such as <code>round(x)</code> or <code>mod(x)</code> are
  more commonly used instead.
</p>

